<STAGE>[A&s;ide to Sir Harry.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Harry.</SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Flutter.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's right. <STAGE>[A&s;ide to Lady Flutter.]</STAGE> What is the matter in debate?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Harry.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, my Lord, 'tis the odde&s;t thing in the world; &s;he is re&s;olved right or wrong, in &s;pite of all I can &s;ay&mdash;to be very good&mdash;and make me love her whether I will or not&mdash;Don't you think that is mon&s;trou&s;ly provoking?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Flutter.</SPEAKER>
<P>And he, my Lord, has taken up as unac|countable a de&s;ign&mdash;of never contradicting me in any thing&mdash;Is not that <HI>as</HI> provoking?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Harry.</SPEAKER>
<P>A'n't we a couple of fools, my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, really, Sir Harry,&mdash;if this could be&mdash;I can't &s;ay&mdash;I am &s;ure I &s;incerely wi&s;h to &s;ee you both in good terms&mdash;and if you have found out a way&mdash;with all my heart.</P>
<STAGE>[Sir Harry and Lady Flutter both bur&s;t out a laughing.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am glad to &s;ee you &s;o merry, my young gentry&mdash;I wi&s;h it may la&s;t, that's all. Sir Harry, I have a word to &s;ay to you. Why you are undone, man, if once you let her turn matters to ridicule.</P>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide to Sir Harry.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Harry.</SPEAKER>
