<STAGE>[A&s;ide to Lord Medway.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Flutter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, I'll have no plotting.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poh, poh, &s;he will get the better of <HI>you</HI> I &s;ee&mdash;<STAGE>[A&s;ide to Sir Harry.]</STAGE> Let <HI>me</HI> &s;peak to her&mdash;Lady Flutter!</P>
<STAGE>[Advances towards her.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Flutter.</SPEAKER>
<P>The tables are turned, my Lord; I'll whi&s;|per with no body but Sir Harry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord.</SPEAKER>
<P>But two words&mdash;When &s;hall we meet?</P>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="60" REF="590">
<SPEAKER>Lady Flutter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never <STAGE>[A&s;ide to Lord Medway.]</STAGE>&mdash;Sir Harry, now that you intend to be very fond of me, I de&s;ire that you will grow a little jealous, and tell my Lord that he mu&s;t not come into my dre&s;&s;ing-room in a morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Harry.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith, my Lord, that's true, I begin not to re|li&s;h the Spartan &s;cheme as well as I did.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mighty fine! this is an extraordinary metamorpho|&s;is, if it holds&mdash;but of that I own I have &s;ome doubt.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Flutter.</SPEAKER>
<P>You need not fear, my Lord&mdash;We have <HI>your</HI> good wi&s;hes that it &s;hould, I know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's home.</P>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Flutter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Sir Harry, I want to go to an auction this morning; will you be &s;o good as to give me your com|pany?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Harry.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart, my dear, I'll attend you; and &s;ee here I received all this to day! <STAGE>[Takes out a pur&s;e, which &s;he &s;natches from him.]</STAGE> Oh you little plunderer! give me a ki&s;s for it&mdash;I'll have another&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Flutter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go, you extortioner&mdash;day, day, my Lord.</P>
<STAGE>[They go out romping together.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can be the meaning of all this? damned little cocquet&mdash;So much art at her years!&mdash;or is it owing to my wife's interpo&s;ition? Yet &s;he knew not of my de&s;ign&mdash;Any way I am a&s;hamed to be ba&s;&s;led &s;o ridiculou&s;ly&mdash;And that puppy Sir Harry too&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>Enter Servant.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Anthony Branville's come to wait on your Lord|&s;hip&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord.</SPEAKER>
